## What Is Theology?

Theology is "faith seeking understanding" (*fides quaerens intellectum*, as Anselm of Canterbury defined it). It begins where philosophy ends: with revelation. Rather than using reason alone to discover truth about God, theology takes divine revelation — scripture, prophets, and inspired tradition — as its starting point and then uses reason to understand, clarify, and defend what has been revealed.

Theology is not blind acceptance. It is rigorous intellectual work done within the context of faith. The greatest theologians — Augustine, Aquinas, Luther — were not less rational than the philosophers; they were rational in the service of revealed truth.

